WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.660
Yeah, as users and developers of open source software, we get to stand on the shoulders

00:00:05.660 --> 00:00:11.200
of giants. That means we can build on the work of others to build something really epic,

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:17.120
maybe like this human pyramid on water skis. But there's a danger that the picture can

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:22.959
look a little bit different, maybe like this famous XKCD cartoon, where we have this towering

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:28.280
jumble of blocks that is balanced precariously on one small piece that represents a project

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:34.480
some random person in Nebraska has been thanklessly maintaining since 2003. I'm sure some of

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:41.720
you, many of you have seen this before. And large open source projects like R or Python

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:47.160
tend to fall somewhere between these two pictures. And I'm going to be focusing in this talk

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:54.040
on R. So if we think about the R Project, we have a small team of core developers that

00:00:54.040 --> 00:01:01.520
maintain the code base that is distributed as R. So this is about 20 people, and only

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:08.599
one of them is working full time on R development, most squeezing this into or alongside their

00:01:08.599 --> 00:01:17.239
regular jobs as academics or data scientists. Beyond that, we have a slightly larger group

00:01:17.239 --> 00:01:23.559
of external contributors that also contribute to the code base, but on a more ad hoc basis.

00:01:23.559 --> 00:01:29.199
And beyond that, we have the massive community of R users and developers that are using and

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:36.320
building on base R, but not necessarily contributing back to the core project. And of course, for

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:42.239
R to be sustainable, we do need people to contribute back in some way to the core project.

00:01:42.239 --> 00:01:47.680
And I'm going to be talking about different ways you can do that. So why should you care?

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:52.480
Well, hopefully you agree with me that R is special, right? It's great. It has the state

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:57.519
of the art statistical methods. You can use it for your full data pipeline. It's a user

00:01:57.519 --> 00:02:04.239
friendly language, and it has a great community. And many of you use it. Maybe you don't necessarily

00:02:04.239 --> 00:02:08.160
realize that you're using base R, but if you're using Tidyverse or Shiny, of course, that's

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:16.279
all relying on the core code base. And you've invested time and money, and you don't want

00:02:16.279 --> 00:02:22.000
that time and money that you invested in skills and the development of code to go to waste.

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:26.919
And finally, R needs your help, like any open source project. Just as an indicator, it has

00:02:26.919 --> 00:02:33.600
over 600 open bugs on its bug tracker. I also sort of slightly alluded to this demographic

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:40.759
cliff that we're facing. So R is a 30 year old project. Many of the core developers are

00:02:40.759 --> 00:02:47.160
near or even beyond the end of their careers. You know, they've retired now, officially.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:51.039
And it's also acknowledged that there's a lack of diversity. So it'd be great to work

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:55.800
on this at the same time as we're thinking about bringing new people in. And what have

00:02:55.800 --> 00:03:01.800
I got to do with it? Well, I'm a similar vintage to Colin. I started using R in 2001, in my

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:07.960
PhD. And I've worked in academia, in pharma, as a freelancer. And in all these roles, R

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:13.800
has been fundamental to my work. A few years ago, I went back to academia to take up a

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:19.240
research software engineering fellowship, where I'm focusing on this issue of sustainability

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:24.479
and diversity and inclusion in the R projects. And in relation to the R projects, I made

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:31.399
my first contribution to base R in 2004, my first real job after the PhD. And as part

00:03:31.399 --> 00:03:38.839
of that job, I was developing a CRAN package. So that was my first CRAN package in 2005.

00:03:38.839 --> 00:03:43.759
And over time, I got more involved in the R community. And 2015, I was elected as an

00:03:43.759 --> 00:03:51.559
R Foundation member. And as one of my tasks on the R Foundation, I co-founded FORWARDS,

00:03:51.559 --> 00:03:57.320
which is the task force for underrepresented groups in the R community. And then in 2020,

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:01.520
I started the R Contribution Working Group, with the aim of fostering a larger and more

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:08.279
diverse community of contributors to R. So there are many ways that you can contribute.

00:04:08.279 --> 00:04:12.320
And it will take some combination of skill, time and money. And I'm going to be using

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:18.600
these icons to give an indicator of the relative skill, time and money that it will take to

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:23.040
get started in the different ways that I mentioned. So I'm not going to go over in detail, but

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:27.959
you'll see the symbols on the slides. There's also lots of links that you can follow to

00:04:27.959 --> 00:04:31.679
get more information about all the things I talk about. And there'll be a QR code at

00:04:31.679 --> 00:04:36.320
the end, so you can grab a copy of my slides and get all those links.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:40.839
Okay, so the first way is the sort of the obvious way, contributing to the code base

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:47.359
itself. But the code base doesn't just include R code. All right, it includes text, the messages,

00:04:47.359 --> 00:04:52.480
warnings and errors that you see when you're using R, includes documentation, the R help

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:58.079
files, but also the R manuals. So the help files are in RD format, the manuals are written

00:04:58.079 --> 00:05:03.480
in a thing called tech info. And then there's code, but it's not just R code. There's a

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:08.720
huge amount of C code in base R, and there's also other languages like Fortran and Bash.

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.600
So many of you will have skills that you can potentially contribute here. So in terms of

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:19.079
text, the main way that you can contribute here is in translating the text from English

00:05:19.079 --> 00:05:24.760
to other languages. And for this, we have a weblaid interface that provides a browser

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:29.160
interface where you can step through the messages that need translation in a particular language.

00:05:29.239 --> 00:05:34.600
So in the example here, we're looking at messages in the R files, the stats package, and we're

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:40.720
looking at translating those to Spanish. So you'll see the message that's the original

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:46.160
English and underneath there'll be a blank box if there's no translation, or there might

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:51.720
be an existing translation that needs a view. And so as a contributor, you can add the translation

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:56.640
or update the translation, save and continue. And those contributions that you make will

00:05:56.640 --> 00:06:06.399
eventually be pulled together and added to. If you want to contribute to documentation,

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:11.640
fixing a typo or making a small improvement to the documentation, you can use the GitHub

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:17.760
mirror. So R itself is maintained in subversion, but there's a mirror of the source code on

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:24.920
GitHub. So you can go over there. It's the RSVN repo on GitHub, and you can find the

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:31.720
source file. So this is the source file for the help on multi-non. And click on the pencil

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:37.399
icons edit file, which you can do all through the browser, and it will open a fork of the

00:06:37.399 --> 00:06:42.920
product for you. You can make your change, then you can make a pull request back to the

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:50.480
repo. And from that, you can create a patch file that you can submit to R-Core for consideration.

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:54.640
You can contribute to the code in a very similar way, but with code, it's a little

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:59.000
bit more complicated. You might want to edit more than one file. And if you're working

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.079
on an internal function or compiled code, then you'll want to rebuild R in order to

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:09.079
see the change. And so for this, we can instead use the R dev container. So this is a virtual

00:07:09.079 --> 00:07:15.279
environment that you can launch through GitHub Codespaces. It has a VS Code IDE. So you can

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:22.040
get a copy in here of the R sources, open the files that you want to edit. So here I've

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:27.799
got the source file for the ask yes, no function. So it's an R script. And I'm just going to

00:07:27.799 --> 00:07:34.839
make a simple change here. So one of the options is one of the default choices that this function

00:07:34.839 --> 00:07:39.959
gives is yes. So the options are yes, no, or cancel. And I'm going to change yes to

00:07:39.959 --> 00:07:45.119
oh yeah. So there we are. I've done it. You can see the old line that has yes. You can

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:49.760
see the new line that has oh yeah. And this is using VS Code's version control features.

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:54.519
So we can see the change. At the moment, I've just changed the source file. But staying

00:07:54.519 --> 00:08:00.000
in the dev container, I can rebuild R. And then I can run my function with the change.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.760
And I can see if it's worked as expected in an example. So you might not, I don't know,

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:09.119
hopefully some of you can read that. So we can see that when I call the ask yes, no function,

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:17.200
I now get oh yeah as one of the options that I should give. So this allows us to test changes

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:24.160
and develop bug fixes, for example, in the code or the documentation that we would like

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:33.599
to propose to R. If you head to the contributor.r-project.org website, you'll find information on a range

00:08:33.599 --> 00:08:38.559
of support for people that want to contribute to R. So we have a Slack group. We have the

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:46.159
R development guide, which is an ebook targeted at people new to contribution covering a lot

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:51.640
of the information that you'll need to know. We also have slides and video tutorials. And

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:56.799
we also have sort of live help. So we have monthly office hours in two different time

00:08:56.799 --> 00:09:02.400
zones. It can drop in and ask for help on getting started or if you've started to work

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:07.559
on a bug fix or something and you want to discuss it. And we also started to organize

00:09:07.559 --> 00:09:13.239
R Dev Days as such nights to conferences. And we'll be having a small group alongside

00:09:13.239 --> 00:09:17.599
the Tidyverse Dev Day on Thursday. And we have a few spaces left if anybody would like

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:23.520
to join us then. So beyond contributing to the code base, there are other ways that you

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:29.359
can contribute your experience and expertise. One way is testing R before release. So you

00:09:29.359 --> 00:09:33.840
may know that R has a major release once a year around April time. A couple of weeks

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:38.000
before that, there'll be a pre-release version that is available on the R project website.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.520
And you can help by testing your own programs and workflows, your special ways of installing

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:48.559
or setting up R, things that interact with external libraries or interactive R packages.

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:53.239
In other words, things that are pretty tricky for the small core team to test themselves.

00:09:53.239 --> 00:09:58.520
And if you find any issues and report those back, you know, maybe they can get fixed before

00:09:58.919 --> 00:10:05.679
the official release. But it's not too late to report issues, of course, after the release.

00:10:05.679 --> 00:10:10.039
And it's really helpful for anybody to report any issue you find on the bug tracker to help

00:10:10.039 --> 00:10:16.119
maintain R to a high standard. So both bug reports and wishlist items, sort of feature

00:10:16.119 --> 00:10:21.880
requests, can be posted on R's Bugzilla. And it's really helpful if you're reporting a

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:26.760
bug to include a minimal reproducible example, which many of you will be familiar with. But

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:31.280
in R, it's particularly helpful to restrict yourself to the base R packages and data.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:36.599
So it's clear that it really is an issue with base R, and it can be easily reproduced without

00:10:36.599 --> 00:10:43.479
any add-on packages. If you've got a little bit more experience and time, then you can

00:10:43.479 --> 00:10:48.280
also help by reviewing bug reports. For example, you can help by trying to reproduce the bug

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:53.919
in different versions of R or in different operating systems, different graphical devices.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:11:00.280
You might be able to simplify the reprex as another step towards analyzing the root cause,

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:04.679
or you might be the one that helps find the root cause. You know, the few lines of R code

00:11:04.679 --> 00:11:10.919
or C where the bug is actually happening. And then you can discuss with others whether

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:15.640
this is something that actually needs fixing and how to fix it. So it helps to have people

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:19.719
contribute to that discussion rather than it just being one person having to think about

00:11:19.719 --> 00:11:25.520
this. You can also contribute your expertise via a working group. So I've also already

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:30.960
briefly mentioned the R Contribution Working Group and FWDs. The R Consortium also runs

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:37.039
a number of working groups, and some of these relate to core development or core infrastructure.

00:11:37.039 --> 00:11:42.479
So I mentioned a few of them here. There's one on thinking about how to implement multilingual

00:11:42.479 --> 00:11:49.000
R documentation. So in other words, having R files, R help files in different languages.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.320
There's one that's been working for a number of years on the R7 package, which is a potential

00:11:54.320 --> 00:12:00.640
successor to S3 and S4 classes and methods in R. And there's the R Repositories Working

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:05.760
Group, which thinks about how to support CRAN and the development of new package repositories

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:14.640
for the community. And finally, I'd like to mention contributing financially. So far,

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:19.440
the contributions have mainly been contributing your time and skill, but of course, money

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:25.200
is also useful. So how can you do that? If you're an organization, the most obvious way

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:32.200
is through the R Consortium, which was basically set up to help businesses support the R ecosystem.

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:37.239
And it has a number of membership levels for different sized businesses. And this funding

00:12:37.239 --> 00:12:44.119
goes towards key infrastructure projects and community conferences and meetups, which have

00:12:44.119 --> 00:12:51.919
been a real boost to the R community. So this is a really valuable contribution.

00:12:51.919 --> 00:12:55.520
There's also the R Foundation, which I've also briefly mentioned. This is the nonprofit

00:12:55.520 --> 00:13:00.599
organization that was set up a long time ago to support R. This works on a bit of a smaller

00:13:00.599 --> 00:13:07.960
scale, but it also has institutional memberships, starting from just €250 a year. But of course,

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:12.159
if you want to contribute more, that's also welcome. And that would also be recognized.

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:19.039
So the highest level is to be a patron with unspecified monetary amounts, and they're

00:13:19.039 --> 00:13:24.479
very happy to say that the deposit is a patron of the R Foundation. And this money goes towards

00:13:25.359 --> 00:13:30.559
funding things that the R projects and the R Foundation are involved in. So some support

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:36.159
for R Core, CRAN, the R Journal, the UseR! Conference, and things like the R Dev Days.

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:40.239
And both the R Foundation and our consortium work together as well.

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:46.479
So for example, they jointly fund one of the R Core members at the moment.

00:13:48.479 --> 00:13:52.000
But you can also contribute as an individual. So the easiest way to do this is through the

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:57.039
R Foundation, which has an individual membership level, or you can make a one-off donation

00:13:57.840 --> 00:14:02.479
of the amount of your choice. We also have an open collective. This was mainly set up

00:14:02.479 --> 00:14:09.359
to receive money from Google Season of Docs. But you can also contribute to that. And that

00:14:09.359 --> 00:14:13.520
funding goes towards small projects, such as maintenance of the R Development Guide,

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:21.679
or the UseR! Info Board that tracks all the information about past UseR! conferences to help

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:28.320
future organizers. So in summary, then, there are quite a number of ways actually

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:34.719
that have a low barrier to entry. Message translation, documentation fixes, testing R,

00:14:34.719 --> 00:14:41.200
reporting bugs, making an individual donation. If you have a little bit more time and expertise,

00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:47.280
then you can get into working on code fixes, reviewing bugs, or contributing to a working

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:53.919
group. And probably the highest barrier is making an institution-level donation. But this makes a

00:14:53.919 --> 00:14:58.320
lot of sense if your institution is relying heavily on R and wants to make sure it's

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:04.000
sustainable for the long term. So here's the QR code I mentioned, which we're taking to these

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.719
slides, and all the links. There's another page after this that is just all the links on one page,

00:15:08.719 --> 00:15:12.719
so you don't necessarily have to go all through the slides again unless you find that helpful.

00:15:13.359 --> 00:15:17.039
And so thank you very much.

00:15:25.039 --> 00:15:31.039
We do have time for a couple questions.

00:15:33.119 --> 00:15:39.280
We have, who comes up with the R version names and how can we submit some suggestions?

00:15:40.239 --> 00:15:47.840
Okay, so yeah, so you might have seen these quirky nicknames for the R versions, and it's

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:52.880
Peter Dalgard, one of the R core members that come up with these names, and they're based on the

00:15:52.880 --> 00:16:02.320
Peanuts cartoons. I don't know if he takes suggestions, but yeah, maybe you would have

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:07.280
to email Peter. He's at the University of Copenhagen, I think, so you could probably

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:12.880
find him online, Peter. And then one more, are there any particular types of contribution the

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:19.039
R core team actively looking for right now? And so some of those things I mentioned are

00:16:19.039 --> 00:16:23.280
things that the R core have particularly asked for, like testing R before release,

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:27.760
helping to review bugs. These are things that they've written about on the R blog,

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:30.799
so that's another way you can sort of follow what's happening in the project.

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:37.599
And they do engage with these activities like the R Dev Day, so we try and find things that

00:16:37.599 --> 00:16:41.840
have R core support, so you've got a good chance of your contributions being accepted.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:44.559
Awesome, thank you so much.

